ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: During the last six months, have you had a panic attack or a sudden rush of intense fear or anxiety?
Notes: 1= Yes; 2= No; 3 = Prefer not to respond; 88=Missing Data

ElementDescription: During the last six months, have you had a panic attack or a sudden rush of intense fear or anxiety? When was the most recent time this occurred?
Was at least one panic attack unexpected, as if it came out of the blue?
Was at least one panic attack unexpected, as if it came out of the blue? Did it happen more than once?
Approximately how many panic attacks have you had in your lifetime?
Have you ever worried a lot (for at least one month) about having another panic attack?
Have you ever worried a lot (at least one month) that having the attacks meant you were losing control, going crazy, having a heart attack, seriously ill, etc.?
Did you ever change your behavior or do something different (for at least one month) because of the attacks?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Shortness of breath or smothering sensations?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Feeling dizzy, unsteady, lightheaded, or faint?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Palpitations, pounding heart, or rapid heart rate?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Trembling or shaking?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Sweating?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Feelings of choking?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Nausea or abdominal distress?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Numbness or tingling sensations?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Flushes (hot flashes) or chills?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Chest pain or discomfort?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Fear of dying?
Think back to your most severe panic attack. Did you experience any of the following symptoms? Fear of going crazy or doing something uncontrolled?
How much do these symptoms interfere with your daily functioning?
Notes: 1= Not at all; 2=Mildly; 3=Moderately; 4=Severely; 5=A moderate amount; 6=A lot; 88=Missing Data

ElementDescription: How distressing do you find these symptoms?
When you have bad panic attacks, does it often take less than ten minutes from the point at which the attack begins, to the point at which it reaches a peak or becomes most intense?
Just before you began having panic attacks, were you taking any drugs or excessive amounts (more than 4 cups daily) of stimulants (e.g., coffee, tea, or cola with caffeine)?

Just before you began having panic attacks, were you taking any drugs or excessive amounts (more than 4 cups daily) of stimulants (e.g., coffee, tea, or cola with caffeine)? What was it that you were taking?

Just before you began having panic attacks, were you taking any drugs or excessive amounts (more than 4 cups daily) of stimulants (e.g., coffee, tea, or cola with caffeine)? How much of it were you taking (in cups, etc.)?
Have you ever been diagnosed with a medical problem (hyperthyroidism, a seizure or cardiac condition, etc.) that could have caused your panic symptoms?
